1. The challenge

At King Arthur’s court, the Green Knight proposes a game:
	1.	Someone may strike him with an axe.
	2.	In one year, they must receive the same blow back.

It sounds harmless because the knight appears supernatural.

So Sir Gawain accepts and cuts off the Green Knight’s head.

Everyone assumes the problem is solved.

But then the knight calmly:
	•	picks up his head
	•	reminds Gawain of the bargain
	•	rides away.

The real problem has just begun.

⸻

2. The deeper lesson

The story is really about deferred consequences.

When Gawain swings the axe, he thinks:

The action ends here.

But the structure of the game means:

Action → Delay → Return

The blow comes back later.

In systems terms:

Input → latency → feedback

The system stores the state.

⸻

3. Why the problem becomes worse

Your interpretation is actually one of the classic readings.

When you think you’ve destroyed the problem, you:
	1.	Stop analyzing it
	2.	Stop respecting it
	3.	Assume it’s finished

But the system still contains the debt.

And now the return blow arrives:
	•	later
	•	stronger
	•	psychologically heavier.

It becomes worse because complacency grows during the delay.

⸻

